📌 1. OSI & TCP/IP Models with Real-World Examples

| **Layer (OSI)** | **Real-World Example**                     | **TCP/IP Mapping** |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------------ | ------------------ |
| Application     | HTTP, HTTPS, DNS, FTP                      | Application        |
| Presentation    | SSL/TLS (encryption)                       | Application        |
| Session         | SSH sessions, API calls                    | Application        |
| Transport       | TCP (file transfer), UDP (video streaming) | Transport          |
| Network         | IP, ICMP (ping)                            | Internet           |
| Data Link       | Ethernet, Wi-Fi (MAC addresses)            | Network Access     |
| Physical        | Cables, radio signals, switches            | Network Access     |

  👉 Example: When you open https://google.com,

Application → HTTPS request

Transport → TCP ensures reliable delivery

Network → IP routes packets

Data Link → Wi-Fi/Ethernet transmits frames

Physical → Your laptop sends signals via Wi-Fi

📌 2. Common Protocols & Ports for DevOps

| **Protocol**  | **Port**  | **DevOps Usage**                 |
| ------------- | --------- | -------------------------------- |
| HTTP          | 80        | Web traffic, app testing         |
| HTTPS         | 443       | Secure CI/CD webhooks, APIs      |
| SSH           | 22        | Remote server login, Git ops     |
| FTP           | 21        | File transfers                   |
| DNS           | 53        | Domain resolution in deployments |
| SMTP          | 25        | Email notifications              |
| MySQL         | 3306      | DB connections in apps           |
| PostgreSQL    | 5432      | DB connections in apps           |
| Docker Daemon | 2375/2376 | Container communication          |

  👉 Tip: Always restrict ports with firewalls/Security Groups to avoid attacks. 🔐

📌 3. AWS EC2 & Security Groups – Step by Step

I. Login to AWS Console → Launch EC2 Instance (Ubuntu Free Tier).

II. Create a Security Group with rules:
	
	Inbound:

		SSH (22) → Your IP

		HTTP (80) → Anywhere

		HTTPS (443) → Anywhere

		Outbound: Allow all (default).

III. Launch instance and connect:

	$ssh -i my-key.pem ubuntu@<public-ip>

IV. Test rules:

	curl localhost
	ping google.com

V. Secure your instance by limiting access only to trusted IPs.

📌 4. Networking Commands Cheat Sheet

| **Command**                                    | **Usage**                       |
| ---------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| `ping google.com`                              | Test connectivity               |
| `traceroute google.com` / `tracert google.com` | Trace packet route              |
| `netstat -tulnp`                               | Show active ports & connections |
| `curl -I https://example.com`                  | Fetch HTTP headers              |
| `dig google.com`                               | DNS lookup (Linux/macOS)        |
| `nslookup google.com`                          | DNS lookup (Windows)            |


  👉 Handy for debugging deployments, DNS issues, and connectivity errors.

